{{Multiple issues| {{Update|date=April 2018}} {{Refimprove|date=April 2018}} }} The number of Indian students studying abroad rapidly increased by 163% between 1999 and 2006 to reach 145,539 as compared to slower growth of 25% between 2006 and 2013 to reach 181,872, according an analysis of UNESCO data. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Choudaha|first=Rahul|date=March 2017|title=Three waves of international student mobility (1999-2020)|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B4RmnCsexL7ZckFpR1FXVFFQZ2M/view|journal=Studies in Higher Education|publisher=Taylor & Francis|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1080/03075079.2017.1293872|via=}}</ref>
Students of Indian origin are [[Student migration|traveling]] in higher numbers than ever before to pursue [[higher education]] abroad. Nearly 85% of internationally mobile Indian students head for five countries—the United States, the United Kingdom, Australia, Canada and New Zealand{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}—but China and Germany are both emerging destinations for Indian students heading abroad, though the numbers heading for Germany are still relatively small. In 2006, of the 123,000 studying outside India, 76,500 chose the US, followed by the UK; in 2001 India overtook China as the source of the largest number of foreign students in the United States.
== Students from India in the United States of America == The number of students studying in the US rose 94,563 to 103,260 in 2010–11.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807081043/http://newdelhi.usembassy.gov/pr112509a.html|url=http://newdelhi.usembassy.gov/pr112509a.html|title=Press Releases 2009: U.S. Welcomes Indian Students, Prepares for PM Singh| date=18 November 2009 |archivedate=7 August 2011|publisher=Embassy of the United States New Delhi, India|accessdate=22 February 2018}}</ref> Most of the students choose either the east coast or the mid-west as their destination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Chennai/TN_applicants_to_US_opt_for_IT_Official/articleshow/3112393.cms|title=TN applicants to US opt for IT: Official - Times of India|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref>
In 2001 India overtook China as the source of the largest number of foreign students in the United States.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/2007/08/05/india-america-students-oped-cz_aaw_0813students.html "More Indians studying abroad"] ''Forbes'', 2007-08-05.</ref> "In the US alone, nearly 45% of international students are either Chinese or Indians. That's almost half the market. Canada seems to be headed that way too. In 2010, the percentage share for China plus India was 30%. In 2014, it was almost 42%", the report noted.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20160601180527213|title=Surge in growth of Indian students studying abroad - University World News|website=www.universityworldnews.com|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref>
== Students from India in the United Kingdom == The number of Indian students studying in the UK nearly doubled between 1999 and 2009,<ref name="Guardian Staff and Agencies">{{cite news | work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2009/sep/24/internationalstudents-students|title = Twice as many foreign students at UK universities| date = 24 September 2009 |accessdate=15 June 2010 | location=London}}</ref> when 19,205 Indian students were studying at UK institutions.<ref name="The Sunday Times">{{cite news | work=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)]]|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100530/Education/ed12.html |title = Why students prefer to study in UK Colleges or Universities | date = 30 May 2010 |accessdate=15 June 2010}}</ref> {{As of|2010|05}}, half of all Indian students in the UK were studying at the [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate level]].<ref name="The Independent">{{cite news | work=[[The Independent]]|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/postgraduate/postgraduate-study/how-life-should-be-made-better-for-overseas-students-1971831.html |title = How Life Should be Made Better for Overseas Students | date = 13 May 2010 |accessdate=15 June 2010 | location=London | first=Harriet | last=Swain}}</ref>
== Students from India in Australia == After peaking in 2009, the number of Indian students studying in Australia fell following racial attacks; by 2015 the number had risen to exceed the 2009 number.<ref name="auto"/> During 2013-14, 34,100 Australian visas were issued to Indian students, a rise of 38% as compared to the previous year.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}
== Students from India in Germany == As of 2014-15, there are approximately 11000 Indian students studying in Germany, comprising 4.9% of international students in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iie.org/Services/Project-Atlas/Germany/International-Students-In-Germany#.WKn1nFeVuk0|title=Project Atlas|website=www.iie.org|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> Numbers are rising. German universities have started offering several master's programs in English, attracting Indian students.
==Other major destinations== Nearly 85% of internationally mobile Indian students head for five countries: the US, UK, Australia, Canada and New Zealand, but in addition to Germany, China, Ukraine, Russia and Georgia are some emerging destination for Indian students heading abroad.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} Romania and Ukraine has also emerged as a destination for Indian students of medicine as the education system is regulated under the [[European Union]] and is of a higher quality than in the countries of the former USSR quality is relatively better compared to Ex-USSR, China, and the Philippines.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}
Many Indian students are also opting for higher education in the Netherlands because of the high quality of education, availability of more than 2,000 courses taught completely in English, and access to the European Union including career opportunities after graduation.<ref>B. S. Warrier, [http://www.thehindu.com/features/education/college-and-university/Study-in-the-Netherlands-for-quality-education/article16853594.ece "Study in the Netherlands for quality education"], ''The Hindu'', December 16, 2009.</ref><ref>[https://www.nesoindia.org/why-study-in-holland "8 reasons to study in Holland"], ''Nuffic Neso'', April 25, 2017, retrieved April 24, 2018</ref> In 2017, approximately 2,021 Indian students went to the Netherlands for higher studies.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}
Many Indians have also chosen to study in Denmark and Norway, which offer many professional courses, and about 100 in Poland.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}
